Comparing and Contrasting Sociological Ideas
	There are many different sociologists and historians who have many different views and ideas. Each sociologist focuses on a different area of study and are working in a different time period, which means that there are many different ways to look at sociological concepts. In addition, as time passes, new problems and ideas arise that lead to new ways to understand sociology and our society today. As a result, different sociologists will have some similar, but also some differing views and explanations for different aspects of sociology. Yuval Noah Harari, for example, will have some similar and different ideas compared to past sociologists such as Émile Durkheim and George Mead. 
	Yuval Noah Harari is an Israeli historian and philosopher, and the author of the book 21 Lessons for the 21st Century. In this book, he addresses our current global climate and looks at big questions faced by today’s society. He thinks about these pressing questions and then addresses them throughout the book. Many of the topics addressed in his book relate to concepts that have been discussed by sociologists. One of the points that Harari argues in his book is that religion is completely irrelevant to policy and technical problems and should not be used to solve them. The examples that he provides for these problems include ideas such as what measures governments should take and how farmers should deal with droughts. In the past, religion was consistently used to solve these problems because people didn’t have the same knowledge that we have today. Given what we now know with modern science and technology, religion would have no way to help solve these problems, and so it should be left out completely. However, Harari states that religion is relevant for problems surrounding identity, and that it contributes to a big part of the problem rather than the solution. Identity problems include things like what we should care about and how we should feel about certain topics. Harari explains how all religious traditions unite the people who follow and distinguishes them from the other people around them that don’t follow the same religion. Religion is what provides people with a template for how they should live their lives and what they should believe in, which creates one group with the same views. He also explains how some religions encourage more kindness and charitability, while others fill the world with more ugliness and cruelty. He is demonstrating how the unity created through religion can be harmful rather than beneficial.
	Émile Durkheim was a French sociologist who studied religion and how it influences our social interactions. Durkheim believed that religion was important to study and understand because he thought that all fundamental categories of thought and science have religious roots. This meant he believed that religion was the backbone for thinking and provided a sort of template for how science and thought were created. He also believed that all great institutions were born in religion. Religion is what helped form our modern institutions and provide them with the foundation to grow into what they are today. In addition, Durkheim believed that religion created a collective representation and consciousness among those who practiced a similar religion. The collective consciousness is the set of common ideas or beliefs held by a certain group. These beliefs that are the same among the whole group act to unify the group. It also works to shape the individual’s perspective on how they should live their life. It guides what someone perceives as meaningful, dangerous, good, or evil. A collective representation is a symbol, artifact, or narrative that articulates and embodies the collective beliefs, sentiments, and values of a certain group. This includes examples such as the idea of giving at Christmas, a cross, or wedding rings. The collective representation is the symbol or identifying factor of the collective consciousness. Durkheim believes that society is then created through the collective conscious. We work together as a group to collectively produce a shared sense of reality and morals. In Durkheim’s mind, religion is a crucial part of how society is created and run. 
	Harari and Durkheim both argue that religion is an important aspect for uniting people and creating a common belief system. However, their differences are evident in whether they believe this collective consciousness is beneficial or harmful to society. Durkheim believes that having a collective consciousness is important in creating a cohesive society. He argues that it is essential to have similar beliefs and values so that you have a way to relate to those around you. The collective consciousness is what allows us to form our society. He also believed that religion was important in creating our modern institutions and ways of thinking, and that without it, we wouldn’t have modern science or thinking. On the other hand, Harari is arguing that this collective consciousness created from religion often goes too far and creates more problems than solutions. Harari believes that when religion becomes involved, there are strong divisions created between individuals as well as groups. Because religion creates such strong beliefs, it often means that the two opposing groups have even stronger divisions. Each person is expected to act exactly how their religion says they should, and no one should sway from this path. This can lead to problems with the two groups working together or finding ways to keep the peace. When neither group is willing to compromise or hear the other groups perspective, a solution will never be reached. In addition, Harari explains how problems can arise when our identity clumps together beyond our sense of experience. 
	George Mead was another sociologist who had ideas that related to Harari’s. Mead worked to develop an idea of how the human self arises. He believed that the self is experienced through internal dialogue between the “I” and the “me”. The “I” and the “me” are both cognitive elements of the mind, but they have different influences. The “I” is the subjective reaction of the mind to stimuli in the environment and comes from emotional responses or actions. It is almost like your reflex or instincts in response to some event. The “me” is the objective evaluation of the “I” reactions and comes from what has been learned about the particular social setting. Mead also believed that the self is experienced indirectly but completely, while the body is experienced directly but incompletely. When we put these factors together, we have a full, conscious experience of our self. We are reacting to our environment and then evaluating that reaction. Mead believed that this conscious experience was important for humans to understand. It is important that we are fully aware of our “self” and the different pieces that influence our self. 
	In addition to the role of religion in society, another issue Harari addresses in his book 21 Lessons for the 21st Century is the dangers of algorithms and technology in our society. He argues that technology will eventually take over jobs that are currently occupied by humans. Eventually, machines and technology will be able to complete almost all of the jobs that humans are responsible for. This means that many people will be out of jobs and will have to train for new, higher-level jobs that technology will not yet be capable of completing. Another major problem that arises through the development of technology is that it will eventually be able to know you better than you know yourself. Once technology understands us better than we understand ourselves, it will be able to monitor and manipulate our feelings. One example Harari provides for this is how companies will be able to use data and technology to target ads specifically towards you. Your preferences will be used to target ads to you in order to help the companies make the maximum profit. Technology takes away our conscious experiences, and simply replaces it with artificial intelligence. Harari stresses that there is a difference between consciousness and intelligence, and it is important that we continue to have conscious experiences. 
	Both Mead and Harari have a similar view in how it is important to have an overall conscious experience. Mead believed that it was important to have a conscious experience of the self through the “I” and the “me”. He argued that in order to fully experience something, all of the different aspects of your “self” had to interact and work together. Understanding the different influences on your overall experience is crucial in having a conscious experience. Similarly, Harari argues how it is important to maintain a conscious experience rather than simply relying on artificial intelligence. Technology can take over our lives and know us better than we know ourselves, but it cannot create a conscious experience. Technology simply has intelligence while humans are the only ones capable of having a true conscious experience. Therefore, Harari is stressing the importance of preventing technology from taking over every aspect of our lives. Consciousness is too important to humans to let technology take it over. 
	There are many concepts in sociology that remain consistent over time, while others seem to change. As our society grows and develops, new problems will arise that will lead to new concepts and understandings to be created. This means that while some sociologists and historians will have similar views, there will be times when they disagree or have ideas that are inconsistent with one another. However, this does not mean that one view is necessarily better than another. Each sociologist can develop an idea that is completely correct, and that doesn’t automatically discredit another person’s idea. We must take into account all concepts and viewpoints when thinking about sociological concepts.

SOC Final Paper
Do you think women and men are treated the same in America? Most people would say yes just because of what year it is and how much we have developed as a society, but even with that being said women are treated very differently from men even if some men don’t even realize it. On this subject, there is a large gender divide. Only around half of males believe that men and women are treated equally in society, while only 34% of women agree. Approximately half of women believe society favors men over women, compared to 36% of men. With that being said some men do not realize it in the same way that women do just because they overlook it and don’t really understand that no matter what women have always been looked at as inferior. 
Something that I have personally experienced with this was actually here at UNCW. My first semester here I was deciding if I wanted to play club volleyball here at UNCW because volleyball has always been something that I love playing and I thought that it would be very good for me and even a way to make some friends. The first day that I went it everyone was just playing king of the court and pick up games and it was really fun. About 30 minutes into playing the boys club volleyball team showed up and wanted to play pick up with us. I did not think anything of it and thought “oh this is going to be fun because I bet they are good”. Whenever the boys team came up to us they started acting kind of weird and I did not think anything of it just because I thought oh well maybe they don’t really know who we are yet. They ended up sitting on the sidelines and just watching us play. Shortly after they came back up to us and were like can we play with you guys and make teams. Of course we said yes and none of us thought anything about it until about 20 minutes into playing one of the boys came up to me and said “I didn’t expect you to be that good at volleyball”. I was really confused because I had no idea who he was and thought to myself well did he expect me to be bad or not know how to play. I kept playing with them and they were constantly complimenting me and saying things like wow you are really good for your height. I know that they did not think anything about that but to me it felt like a backhanded compliment because they were straight up telling me that they didn’t think I was going to be good and I know it was just because I was a girl. 
Eventually, I put two and two together and realized that they just expected me to not be as good or be able to keep up and actually play a good game with them just because I was a girl. I know that mens volleyball is a lot different than women at the professional level but anything other than that girls can usually keep up with a boys team or at least everytime I have played a boys team I have been able to. The boys team looked at us girls as weak and did not expect us to be good so they just were not even going to play with or ask us to play with them only until they saw us play. That honestly bothered me so much just because the boys came in and just assumed that we were not going to be good I guess and looked at us as inferior to them just because we were girls. It is just crazy to me how the boys do not even realize what they are saying because they don’t look at it the same way girls do just because they are boys and automatically assume that they will be better at sports and don’t think that girls can keep up with them. 
​​Darwin upheld the gender stereotypes of his period in print, most prominently in "The Descent of Man." In that 1871 research of sexual selection, he concluded that a man achieves "a higher eminence, in whatever he takes up" than a female. Meanwhile, he argued that a woman's intuitive abilities are "typical of the lower races." We have talked about gender in society a lot in class and also about different scientists who talk about it and have theories. We read “The Yellow Wallpaper” by Charlotte Perkins Gilman, which is a story based on the nineteenth centuy, for questions in class and that article really stood out to me just for the sole fact that the wife in this story was just looked at as women and not even a person just because of her gender and her husband sees himself as more powerful than her. The narrator was married to a man who dominated her and treated her like a child. Her husband was the primary decision maker, and she lived in a society where women were not permitted to dispute their husbands' judgments. He loves and cares for his wife, but their unequal connection stops him from genuinely understanding her and her issues. He contributes to her destruction by treating her as a "case" or a "wife" rather than a person with a free choice, which is the last thing he wants. The husband in the story did not even realize the way that he was treating her was not fair and because of that the wife was miserable and felt like she had no power and could not do anything. ​​Although the narrator perceives John as cautious and kind at times, she also sees him as arrogant and manipulating at other times. The narrator eventually regards John as her jailer. While prevailing over her supposed escape from the nursery wallpaper, she eventually loses her sanity. I think that this story really expresses gender roles the best just because her husband truly did love her but just because of society and because he was a man he did not realize that he was treating her unfairly and gave her no say in their relationship. 
We also read “ Women as Other” by Simone de Beauvoir which has the same concept about women being treated differently than men. De Beauvoir claims that the fundamental concept of  'woman' is a male concept. Woman is always 'other' because the male is the 'seer' which means he is the subject and she is the object. Beauvoir's focus on the necessity for women to have access to the same activities and projects as men positions her in the liberal, or second-wave feminism tradition. She insists that women be regarded on an equal footing with men, and that laws, practices, and education be changed to support this. This article also stood out to me because men look at women kind of like objects and just as something fun for them, which is the reason why women get objectified so much by men or looked at as weak and not having power. 
In conclusion, men may believe that women are treated the same as women just because of where we are today in society and how things actually have changed so much, but in reality there are still some underlying assumptions about men being superior to women even when they do not realize it. I have personally experienced this in college and definitely have many more times than that. Perkins and Beauvoir explain about it very well in their narratives and writings by talking about things that have actually happened and even giving numbers and percentages to prove their points. I think that in today's society the way women are treated is way better than it used to be, but we still are not treated completely equal like we should be even if men think that we are. Women have always been looked at as inferior to men even if men do not even try to think about it like that. Women are looked at as weak and just as something for mens entertainment which is why they objectify women all the time without even trying. No matter what happens women will be looked at inferior just because of how women used to be treated and that is not fair because women can do anything that a man can and should be recognized for all the things that we can do instead of just being looked at as an object and someone who is weak and powerless.

Sociology 101
Reflection Essay 1
For many people, getting hired at their first job is one of the most exciting experiences. You’ve filled out the application, put down all your assets, recommendations, and now, you await a response. Getting the phone call that you’ve received your desired position makes you feel accomplished, especially while juggling high school and extracurriculars, and you realize that all your hard work has paid off. Receiving the position initially is impressive, while typically you are competing against others, however, maintaining your position at the same workplace is even more impressive than emerging victorious throughout the hiring process. 
I have worked at my school’s after school program for four years throughout highschool. Most of my tasks once I clock in after the final school bell rings include helping children with homework and communicating with parents over the phone or in person while simultaneously making sure children aren’t shoving each other down while they play. Because of my many years of experience, I was able to participate in training new workers, and having some input on new applicants to the program. Recently, I discovered shocking news that is unsettling to myself and should be unsettling to society’s collective consciousness (Durkheim) as well.  Although I have worked with this program longer than any of my other coworkers, I am getting paid $1.20 less than some of my fellow coworkers. This information truly puzzled me, and I began to ask myself  “Why am I receiving less pay for all the time I have spent here, when I’ve been here the longest and have barely received a raise?” After conversing with the only other female that works alongside me, we realized that the two of us were being paid the exact same amount, while our male coworkers were receiving $1.20 higher. Why are the women of this establishment being treated unequally while possessing either the same tasks as the males, or even more than them?
The only disgusting conclusion that I have been able to muster regarding this situation is that I have been “other[ed]” (de Beauvoir) inside my workplace without even realizing it. As de Beauvoir discusses in her essay, “The Second Sex”, about women being “other[ed]” throughout history. Throughout this essay, she criticizes the collective consciousness of society, and how with regards to women, the same beliefs about female inferiority have been collectively held since the beginning of time, starting with religion. De Beauvoir quotes Poulain de la Barre, who discusses how male Jews thank God during their prayers that they were not born a woman. This prayer places so many questions in my mind. Why would these men not want to be a woman so badly that they thank their God for being a male? Is it because they realize as a whole, men are subjugating women?
After finding out this information, I immediately went to my boss in case the unequal pay was a mistake, or perhaps something that was accidentally overlooked. I approached my female boss after work, asking to speak with her in private with the hope that I could resolve this issue occurring at my workplace. However, to my astonishment, the conversation was shut down immediately when I expressed that I was inquiring about unequal pay. I was not even given the opportunity to express my thoughts on the matter, and was told to not discuss my pay with my coworkers again. During this conversation with my boss, I saw a side of her that I had not seen before. This conversation proved to me in a more personal light how the collective consciousness can truly transform a person’s belief, and this especially shocked me since my boss is a woman. I truly would have thought she could relate to me, and realize something unfair was happening, however I was proven wrong by this conversation. 
Afterwards, I felt defeated. I felt as if my voice didn’t matter, but I recognized that my rights were not being respected. I could not figure out why, and I didn’t understand why me not getting the pay I deserved was being shoved under the rug. I could only assume that I was being paid less because I am a woman. I do my job, arguably better than my other coworkers, and never cause any trouble. De Beauvoir quotes Montaigne in her text, “It is easier to accuse one sex then to excuse the other”. I believe that it is easier to punish female coworkers inside the workplace than to change the ideals of the collective consciousness. It is more convenient for those in control of the ideas held in the collective consciousness to allow society to punish women in every aspect of their lives. 
The issue of unequality for women is not a new topic in society’s collective consciousness. There have always been laws, “traditions”, or ideals that have subjugated women, and there was no way for women to defend themselves. Like in my situation, I felt as if there was no way I could defend myself. After being shut down by my boss, I contemplated giving up or not. I feared that me speaking my feelings again would lead to me losing my job. Half of me wanted to stay quiet, but the other half knew that staying quiet is what my workplace wanted me to do. They wanted to get away with the inequality occurring, and not have to change their beliefs about equal pay. 
Oddly enough, in my history class, we were discussing feminism during the time these events were happening. I expressed what was happening to my entire class, and my male teacher, who was enraged by the fact I was getting paid less. My other coworker who was also getting paid less was in this class, and she told her side of the story to him as well. What angered my teacher the most was the fact that when my boss was approached, she denied my request. After talking with us in private after class, he told us he was going to the principal to discuss this matter because she overlooked the summer camp and after school program. He recognized the inequality and admitted it, while my boss refused to. 
A few weeks go by, and my boss approaches my friend and I, asking to talk after work. Honestly, I assumed she was going to fire us, and tell us that we crossed some sort of boundary by discussing our pay amongst ourselves and with faculty members. However, this meeting truly resolved nothing. The only thing my boss was able to offer us is that she would talk with our administrator, and see what she could do about getting our issue resolved. This did not give me much hope, because I was not sure if this would actually happen, or if she would even attempt to resolve this issue . However, the fact that my teacher had gone to the principal about our issue did give me some sort of hope that this could possibly be resolved, or that it would act as an example for future females in the workplace at school. Even after all of this, I was still left with the question: Why is this happening? Why are women being treated unfairly, and why is no one doing anything about it?
There is no found explanation as to why women and men are treated unequally in society. People might say “that’s just how it has always been”, but for me, that is not an explanation at all. Simply saying “that’s how life works” just seems like a lousy excuse for people that do not want to fight the beliefs of the collective consciousness and truly dissect why these types of things are happening to women. De Beauvoir quotes Dorothy Parker in The Second Sex, “Men as well as women, should be regarded by human beings”. There should be no superior or comparison, when in reality, we are all human. De Beauvoir says herself, “[Women] do not authentically assume a subjective attitude”, but it is something that society has conformed to believing themselves. It is evident that my boss has conformed to these ideas about women because she sees no problem with paying my friend and I less than the males that we work with. 
The issue of my friend and I’s unequal pay was never resolved. We were never provided with more information as to why we were being paid unequally, and we were never spoken to about it again. After this past summer, I quit working at the summer camp. I refuse to work someplace where I have dedicated more time and energy than any of my other coworkers, and still be denied an explanation as to why I am being denied the pay I deserve. If this issue was due to a behavioral problem, or my inability to provide work to the program’s standards, I would have been asked to leave instead of getting paid less. I would have been spoken to about my inadequacy for the job, and been asked to leave. I almost wish that this had instead been the reason I was receiving a lesser pay, but because this issue was never resolved and the response from my boss when I first approached her, I know that I was being paid less because I am a woman. It was almost too coincidental that the two women at the program were being paid less than the men for it to not have been the reason. I was “othered” in my workplace, then refused an explanation. I can also infer that this situation was gender based because my male teacher was able to bring attention to this situation, but I was not, when I was actively being victimized and “othered”, yet my opinion was not enough to cause a change. De Beauvoir comments throughout her text that there really has never been an explanation as to why the collective consciousness supports the idea that women are inferior, and every time that there is an attempt at an explanation, the explanation has been “dictated by men’s interest”. This statement in itself raises too many questions for me to even begin to discuss, but supports the statement that those in the superior position, which just so happens to be men, are able to dictate the gap between men and women. 
The idea that men and women are unequal will not change until the beliefs of the collective consciousness change. It is this reason that women are still being paid less, not receiving equal job opportunities, and our rights are being thrown around in congress by men who do not have a say. The inequality between genders is an ongoing argument fueled by the collective consciousness that is trapped in a vicious cycle. When I turned in my two weeks notice, I informed my boss I was quitting due to my rights not being fulfilled at this workplace. I hope that in the future, my step towards equality for women will be appreciated, and not viewed as a cowardly exit to those in society, and it will force them to question the catalysts that led to my resignation.

Healthcare: A Place of Oppression
	It is a common experience between women to be ignored when your pain is at an all time high. Whether it is menstrual cramps or an undiagnosed chronic illness, women are repeatedly ignored and brushed to the side for being “too much” and “overdramatic” when it comes to pain. After hearing these phrases over and over, a woman may start to believe this and push their pain to the sides; complying with the stereotype that women are indeed too dramatic and that they really have nothing to be complaining about. In modern day times, women are told that their pain is not as bad as it seems, due to the place they have been put into by men as the “others” or secondary counterparts. Women must push past these boundaries to make themselves heard as individuals. 
	This argument continued until the nurse finally gave in and tested Mary for a kidney infection. While nurses are usually supposed to take the sample and then move to another room to test, the nurse gathered the sample, looked Mary in the eyes and said, “I’m going to test this in front of you to prove that there is nothing wrong with you.” The nurse tested the sample, and of course, Mary had a kidney infection. After the results came back, the nurse still acted cold and unsympathetic towards Mary, even though Mary was right about her own symptoms. She had to fight a nurse, someone whose job it is to help people and believe their patients to even get a test and receive the medical care she needed to feel better and to get the medication she needed. To make matters even more confusing, the nurse was a woman, but because she was educated and trained by a system that favors men, she still brushed Mary off. If Mary had perhaps been a man, her symptoms would have immediately been listened to, and she would have been tested and treated promptly. This situation explains the way that women are treated as “others” and overlooked because they aren’t considered individuals, but rather counterparts to their men. 
	In Woman as Other, Simone DeBeauvoir explains the position of women in comparison to men. As a feminist and a student of social theory and modern philosophy, she can understand the female struggle, and why that struggle exists in almost every social situation. DeBeauvoir lived through this type of oppression through the scope of a upper class perspective. She interprets the roles of women and men in the modern world thoroughly and states, “He is the Subject; he is the Absolute. She is the Other” (DeBeauvoir 260). This is a perfect explanation of women when they are compared to men. DeBeuvoir explains the role of women in society within her writing, especially as simply a counterpart to men. She also explains that women often play into these roles, as they have been convinced by societal norms that they are the “others”, and their opinions have no relevance. 
	Women find breaking out of this entrapment to be difficult. As explained in Woman as Other, women tend to have no shared stories, religion, past, or sense of community like other communites such as African Americans, those of Jewish descent, and immigrant workers. A woman is completely alone in her own world, and while different women might be experiencing the same situations, they would never know because it has been instilled in modern women that they should not be complaining about their issues, but instead staying quiet and subdued for the men around them. DeBeauvoir states, “They live dispersed among men, tied by homes, work, economic interests, and social conditions to certain men – fathers or husbands – more closely than to other women” (DeBeauvoir 261). Women are so disconnected from their own selves that they become disconnected from the women around them, even though most women suffer from the same oppression daily. 
	While the way that Mary was treated in a place of medical care is inexcusable, it is expected. Since the nurse was a women pushed into a career typically controlled by men, she is so disconnected from her patients (especially women) that she can’t believe a woman fully when they say they are in extreme pain. When women play into this stereotype, this enforces their role as the “other”. Playing into this stereotype also continues to allow men to stand on the pedestal of being the “Absolutes”. Men’s words are law, as show throughout history, and when they say that a woman is overreacting to pain, they must be right. It is often difficult to not play into this stereotype unfortunately. I find that even I do it when talking about an injury because, often, a man in the conversation will counter the pain with the question of “But have you even had this happen to you?” or something similar. After hearing this so many times, it is easier for women to just stay silent in the way that men want them to be rather than expressing more pain or discomfort and sticking up for themselves. 
	It is a common tactic for men to push women to the side, especially when they are talking about their own personal pain. Simone DeBeuvoir explains it best when she labels women as “others”. Healthcare is a place in which a woman can be completely brushed off when she should be listened to and taken care of, which puts women into this “other” position. It is not “over dramatic” to complain about pain, men do it all the time. To tell women that they need to stop complaining about something that isn’t that bad is to play into the stereotype that women should be silent and submissive, the perfect woman for a man or their “One”. While Mary’s story may seem unbelievable, women suffer from this sort of treatment every day in the medical field. Whether their pain is mild or the most excruciating feeling they have every felt, women deserve to feel heard and cared for in the world today.

The “Beauty Myth” and its Effects on a Woman’s Life
	Before a child is even born, there are already plans and standards created for the child. The standards for each child differs around the sex of the baby. For instance, little girls are raised around the standard that if a boy is mean to you, he likes you - that it is just dandy to absorb insults from a male. Why is it that boys aren’t raised in the same manner? To be constantly thinking about the interactions they have with girls, to live up to women’s standards? 
For women, the standards end up being more costly in comparison to men. Women end up sacrificing their lives in order to please a man; to raise a family, to feed the family, clean up after a family, not to go to school, to dress properly, to not act provocatively, to judge others that act out of character - those who are not womanly - it’s seen as a competition. The saying that women live in a man’s world is correct, slowly adapting to change, but is still valid in today’s circumstances. Still valid in my life directly. 
My family pushed classic feminine and masculine traits on my siblings and I. My mother didn’t go to college and she met my father at a job. After they got married and had my brother, Jack, my mother was deemed the one to stay home and raise Jack while my father worked. Growing up watching my mother take care of us, I thought that this is what I was supposed to do in life. That taking care of my husband and kids is all that I would do. At the time, I thought that the purpose of life was that - now, I am absolutely terrified of falling into that trap. My mother didn’t have much say during political discourse over dinner; how women should live their lives, what is a respectable woman, how men should be the ‘man of the house,’ etc. My brother usurped these ideologies from my father and my mother didn’t reject anything, encouraging him through silence. 
Growing up, I was definitely pushed to do girlier things. My neighbor that I had playdates with, Cecelia, decided to stop hanging out with me because I was too boyish. I played soccer for the majority of my life and she thought that I should be partaking in girlier sports like cheerleading. Because I played soccer competitively, I was very fit and muscular. Being muscular, more than some of the boys, I would be seen as masculine and not attractive. Boys in elementary school were not a fan of girls who were confident and beat them in sports or P.E. games. The boys would then draw a liking to the classic feminine girls. No one in elementary school likes playing the part of the odd girl out. That said, I moderated my life to still play soccer and look the way that I did, but I acted more feminine; more flirty, paying my attention to boys and if they liked me or not. As soon as I started acting that way, I started gaining popularity. 
As I got older, things changed. In middle school, I started becoming a woman; I got my period, I developed breasts, I was taller than some of the boys, the whole shabang. Because of this, I matched the current beauty standard that derived from the Kardashian/Jenner family. I became curvy and I was “distracting” the boys in my class. Social Media Affects Body Image Perceptions 
	Social media has easily taken over the minds of many as it has become more accessible and easier to use. Since social media is open for anyone, people can post whatever they want and can post as much as they want. There are no guidelines for what people are allowed to post which creates a free-for-all environment. This being said, social media can create a toxic environment as people tend to flash their perfect lives which leads others to believe a false persona. These face-tuned pictures make viewers feel bad about their bodies, and they become envious of these strangers because they have what seems to be a perfect body. Women tend to only post pictures where they look beautiful in the eyes of today’s standards so they can be praised and feel like they too fit the “perfect body type.” The most recent issue that social media has harmed is women’s body image. People are seeing pictures of half-naked women who have the “perfect body” and the comment sections are flooded with questions about how to get that figure, praises of how perfect their life looks, and comments about how jealous people are of them. Today women are pressured to look a certain way because all they see on social media are pictures of skinny women who have the “perfect body.” Throughout this paper, I will discuss how social media is negatively affecting women’s body images and introducing widespread insecurities and set back in women’s progression for feminisms. 
	During the semester we talked about Naomi Wolf and the Beauty Myth which discussed how images of beauty are used against women. The literature emphasizes how women’s appearance makes women inferior to men in society and how women are held to an unreasonably high beauty standard. This beauty standard has harmed women and how they perceive themselves as comments are made about how they should look and dress in public. Wolf says that women are held to these standards because women are held too old, devaluing traits like being known as a household helper, or a mother. Social media has contributed to the idea of women needing to look a certain way and this affects women’s thoughts about their bodies and how they see themselves.  
	Social media is so powerful because there is so much distance between the viewer and the poster. This distance allows for many messages to be misinterpreted as the interaction is solely online. People also believe that because they are behind a screen, they can post anything they want. The people who post on these platforms don’t see how their content affects their viewers which gives them the power to keep posting what they want. If the people who post don’t know they are hurting anyone then why would they stop posting? 
Another factor that makes mass media a culprit of women’s body issues is the interactivity involved in it (Perloff 2014). Anyone is allowed to interact with the post and leave a comment saying whatever they please. Words on a screen aren’t always perceived how the writer intended them to sound which is where many people tend to get hurt. Social media is also an “immensely more personal outlet than conventional impersonal mass media” (Perloff, 2014). People can relate posts to their life and take the words said more personally. This opens the door for self-comparison and the creation of body insecurities. Social media platforms are also open for viewing and posting 24/7, which gives women the opportunity to constantly compare their bodies to others and feel discomfort in their own skin (Perloff, 2014).
	According to Hogue’s and Mills’ study (2019), when people interact with “attractive peers’ appearance-based social media” posts they are more likely to have a worsened self-body image. Interaction is a key part of this because it shows that people are actively trying to compare themselves to the person in the post. Many people interact when they come across body image posts because they want to know how a person looks a certain way so they can try to achieve that ideal body too. This comparison is detrimental to one’s health because it brings feelings of self-doubt and inadequacy. The downside of social media is the secrecy behind it. Certain posts could be photoshopped and touched up in a million different ways to make the women look “beautiful,” but the viewer would never know. Without this knowledge, the viewer will feel insecure and have a poor mindset about how she looks. 
	In “The Beauty Myth” Wolf talks about “beauty pornography” which links commodified beauty to sexuality. Wolf (1991) claims that this concept has entered into mainstream media and is undermining “women’s new and vulnerable sense of sexual self-worth.” According to Peter and Valkenburg (2017), sexual content in the media has grown bigger in the most recent decades which means more people are being exposed to these unrealistic beauty standards. Social media is the perfect platform for people to post their bodies and show off their figures for anyone to see. However, more women are photoshopping and altering their pictures to fit social media’s beauty standards. This is what is creating the commodified beauty that Wolf is talking about. Some social media posts promote eating disorders and “invasive, potentially deadly "cosmetic" surgeries” that will help women get the perfect body (Wolf, 1991). Without knowing it our society is connecting manufactured beauty with sexuality and body image disorders. These sexual posts create negative body image thoughts in women’s heads because all they see in the media are skinny perfect women. Additionally, when women view such posts, they think that this is the way all women look, yet this is quite incorrect. Women tend to collectively think that they are larger than all the other women around them, but this is far from true. All women, if not most, feel the same insecurities about wanting to change their body, no matter their weight. Unfortunately, all women are in the same boat about wanting to change to fit into the media's beauty standards. Even the skinny models that are being highlighted by the media feel pressure to be skinnier so they can still fit into the beauty standard. If all women feel the same about wanting to look appealing in the eyes of the media, then all women should understand that everyone is different, and everyone should be able to be comfortable in their own skin. 
	Social media has also started to objectify women, reducing their importance to their “sexual appeal in terms of their outer appearance” (Peter & Valkenburg, 2017). Our society has also put women’s sexual activities as the most important criteria for their attractiveness and has made women out to be “sexual playthings waiting to please men’s sexual desires” (Peter & Valkenburg, 2017). Most media content today displays women’s bodies in a way where certain body parts are emphasized which sends an underlying message. Social media tends to define women by their looks and advertising that women’s bodies should look a certain way so that males find them attractive. Wolf (1991) notes that we are using “images of female beauty as a political weapon against women’s advancement.” By putting out the idea that women’s bodies need to look a certain way so that other people, especially men, will find them attractive makes people feel insecure about their looks. Women are even pushing this notion on to other women as they post sexualized pictures of their skinny, perfect bodies on social media. Wolf (1991) believes that we are halting our progression of feminism by letting this beauty myth “poison our freedom” and letting women believe that they need to look a certain way to be appealing to others. 
	In a study done by Grabe et al. (2008) it was said that body dissatisfaction has risen as a “core aspect of women’s physical and mental health.” This study also points to the media as the culprit of body insecurities as it shoves images of thinness onto our society. The images of women that are being shown in today’s media are thinner than in the past, thinner than the actual female population, and thinner than the criteria needed for anorexia (Grabe et al., 2008). This is creating an unattainable goal that is starting to become fanaticized. This study also discovered that media exposure is linked to decreased levels of body satisfaction in women. Moreover, it was concluded that exposure to the thin body type has become more present in the 2000s than it was in the 1990s (Grabe et al., 2008). Social media is a predominant factor in this claim as it allows for the fast-paced spread of ideas and creates a toxic environment. Even Wolf (1991) states that women would “rather lose ten to fifteen pounds than achieve any other goal.” Women nowadays have more power, money, and legal status than they have ever had in the past, yet they physically feel worse about themselves now than any woman before them has ever felt (Wolf, 1991). It’s unfortunate to hear that women have come so far in their struggle for gaining rights and respect just to be brought back down because of the way their bodies look.

Naomi Wolf’s literature perfectly complements the ideas of the negative impacts that social media has on women’s body satisfaction. Wolf believes that women’s beauty is being used as a weapon against them and their progression in feminism is being halted as women are again being reduced to their bodies. Women have come so far in their fight for equality and now their main roadblock is their own bodies. Female beauty is a weapon that is being used against all women and the worst part is, is that women are doing this to other women (Wolf, 1991). Social media enables this by allowing anyone to post whatever content they want for all to see. The lack of connection between the poster and the viewer brings upon miscommunication and secrets which creates an untruthful and negative environment. This is vital because social media is distorting how people look which creates confusion among the female community. Women have started to post more about their bodies and the images of women being shown by the media are more sexualized and show off the thin perfect body type. People are becoming envious of other body types and are developing insecurities and dissatisfactions with the ways they look. Today’s notions of beauty are getting out of hand and leading women to go to extreme measures just to fit into today’s beauty standard. Social media is evidently the leading factor in women’s insecurities as it is using women’s beauty as a weapon against women as a whole and is setting back feminism progression.

Stopping each other from changing roles in turn prevents our society from seeing any real change with social issues.

The confident, more outgoing personality that shined most of the time was suddenly gone whenever I was around my teammates. 
	One sociological concept I have been able to observe throughout my own experiences (and especially at softball) is Goffman’s presentation of the self. Erving Goffman, a Canadian sociologist, suggested the idea that the self is collectively produced. What he meant by that was that as a society we live life on a stage and are actors performing different roles. Our interactions with everyone else performing are what defines our own role and performance in the situation. The different factors like setting, environment, and people involved all work together to create the overall performance. In any interaction, each and every one of us has a certain role to play. For example, a student’s role is to prepare for, attend, and participate in class, and to complete any assigned work outside of class. The teacher’s role is to prepare the lesson, lead class discussions, and prepare students to complete assignments. Together, the students and teacher are actively giving a performance in the classroom. The teacher’s actions and attitude affect how the students act, and how the students are acting impacts how the teacher teaches the class. Additionally, the role we play is greatly influenced by the situation we are in. In a social interaction, if one person does not take part and play their role, then the rest of the performance is thrown off. As the actors in the performance, we take cues from our environment and others around us to determine what our role is in a certain situation. For example, if we are surrounded by close friends and family, we might act more comfortable and informally; a greeting in this setting might be a hug. In contrast, when we meet someone new or are in a business setting, we might act in a more professional manner; a greeting in this situation will most likely be a firm handshake. How we act and the role we play greatly depends on the conditions created by everyone involved. One of the most important aspects of these social performances is a collective understanding of the situation and each other’s roles. Everyone must be aware of the definition of the situation, or the role that each person involved is trying to achieve. It is an expectation that everyone involved is invested in making everyone else’s role appear credible. If a role is discredited or someone misunderstands a role, that is when embarrassment occurs. All our different interactions and performances are unique, which requires us to work together to validate everyone’s roles and ensure a smooth performance.

I quickly realized two different things were happening that were combining to prevent me from really stepping into my new role at softball. The first was that my own fear of embarrassment was preventing me from continuing to try to be myself at practice. I was worried that because I had held a certain role for so long, that my new role would be discredited, leading to me becoming embarrassed. The second thing I noticed was that the other people involved weren’t letting me change my role within the context of softball. My teammates had also grown to expect a certain role from me and changing their understanding of my role could have caused an overall misunderstanding and embarrassment. Because of this, it was easier for them to trap me in a certain role rather than take the risk of allowing a new role and potentially creating a problem in the overall situation. 
Since my teammates weren’t open to change, I was unable to shift into a new role. Our group collectively defined my personal role in our overall performance, which in turn prevented change in that performance from occurring. My personal example from softball is just one of many instances where society has made it difficult for change to occur. Considering Goffman’s idea that the self is collectively produced, it is essential that everyone involved in a certain situation allows for change to occur. Thinking about larger issues in our society such as racism and gender bias, it is clear that change has been difficult and prolonged. For example, racism has always been evident in the United States. Even though we have progressed to abolish slavery and grant rights to African Americans, they still face oppression and injustices in everyday life. Not everyone in society is open to a change in roles for minority groups which makes it extremely challenging for any change to occur. Despite a number of people being open to change, and even fighting in favor of it, if everyone involved is not fully invested in these changing roles, problems will arise. It is very common in our world today for us to collectively prevent someone’s role from changing in order to avoid any possibility of embarrassment or overall problems in the social setting. If, as a society we want significant change to occur, we must first understand that our social interactions have a significant impact on our own self-identity. We must learn how our own actions and beliefs influence how others feel and act when we are with them. Continuing to prevent others from changing their role will stop any sort of progress or change from occurring in our society.

Is an NFL Quarterback more valuable than a paramedic saving lives? While the impulse reaction for most would be to claim the paramedic is more important, looking at wages tells a different story. These two roles and their disparity in wealth and power provide a clear example of the class system. In America, the class system provides too much power and control to those at the top while leaving barely anything left for those below them.
The disparity in power and wealth in America’s class system is not exclusive to the comparison of professional athletes and medical workers. Growing up, I’ve witnessed and experienced the pitfalls of the class system firsthand. I was raised in a family that would probably be most closely defined as lower middle class, and both of my parents worked very hard. My dad worked as a mechanic doing serious physical labor every day, and my mom worked late hours as a nurse. Despite all their hard work, this was still only enough to provide the necessities to our family, which I’m very grateful for. I have had to take out loans for college and I hope to pay them off as soon as I can after graduation.
Witnessing my mom come home on weekends past 2 am and dad clearly exhausted after every shift left a strong impression on me. While our financial situation wasn’t strong, the effort they put into their jobs was admirable. I know I’m not alone in this struggle, as I have friends who relate. Many of the families in my community struggled to make ends meet, and as a kid we were never able to splurge on lavish vacations or cars like our fellow classmates. I am super appreciative of my parents’ hard work, but my family’s situation has been a strong indicator of a major issue with America’s class system.
Seeing how hard my parents worked and how little return on their labor was given was frustrating, to say the least, and inevitably made me somewhat bitter towards the class system in America. Ever since I was a kid, the American Dream has always been preached to me, promising infinite possibilities if I work hard. The longer I’ve lived though, the more I’ve learned that it’s those at the top who have the greatest freedom and power. Wealthy “super-celebrities” like Mark Zuckerburg, Elon Musk, and Jeff Bezos are frequently on the news, announcing new acquisitions, ventures, or even going to space. Measuring income, the richest 0.1% earn 196 times as much as the bottom 90%(inequality.org, 2020). These elite and their counterparts have so much power, as well as financial and informational control, that their continued domination seems unavoidable.
William Domhoff discusses the class system, specifically the class-domination theory of power in his article. Those at the top of the class system, as referenced in my experiences, are referred to by Domhoff as the social upper class. Within the upper class, leaders of subgroups in this category are referred to as the “power elite”. These power elites are able to ensure their continued domination in America by controlling the organizations they lead to benefit themselves. This level of control is one of the ways the upper class maintain their place and continue to oppress the working class in America. 
In addition to control over businesses and organization from Domhoff’s power elite, another way they have control over the country is through the government. Those in the top of the class system have tremendous funding and resources to push policies beneficial to themselves through lobbying, gifts, and promises. While heavily frowned upon, this practice is very successful at implementing the upper class’s ideal policies into the government. When rules and structures are put into place that keep power in the elite’s hands, all lower classes suffer as a result. 
Through these strategies the power elite Domhoff describes employ, it’s clear why inequality is only rising in America, and why it’s so prevalent. Families like mine can work very hard, but will simply never have the tools or control to prosper like the upper class does. While any level of success requires effort, the disparity in wealth in America is not even remotely about who’s working harder. Under the current class system in America, unfairness and mass inequality is an inevitable outcome that will oppress anyone not on top.
Another topic Domhoff discusses is the weakness of the working class in America. The working class make up a vast majority of the country’s population, yet have relatively little power. Domhoff notes that historically, despite the country making lots of social progress, including civil rights, feminism, and support for the lgbt community, the power of the working class has regressed. In fact, between 1962 and 1990, the ratio of business executive pay to that of their workers skyrocketed from 41 to 1 to 300 to 1. While many factors influence policy in the United States, the working class simply is overmatched in terms of finance. In America, those with the money have the resources to keep it. The working class has to make ends meet with their small share, and often there is little remaining after necessities are purchased.
While some inequality is a healthy part of any economy, I believe that the degree America has reached under the class system has crossed a line. The top 1% making more than a hundred times that of the bottom 90% reflects the two ends of a spectrum, where some don’t have enough things to buy, while many families including mine struggle with bare necessities. 
In the case of NFL Quarterbacks making tens of millions of dollars, they very quickly find themselves in the top tier of the upper class. They can then use this money to invest and build even greater wealth. On the other end of the spectrum, paramedics are being worked to death and likely barely make enough to survive. While the professional athlete isn’t necessarily working harder, or striving towards the American dream any more than the paramedic, the two occupations provide two opposite outcomes in terms of compensation. Under the American class system, the gap between these two workers will only grow with each consecutive year.
The 875 to 1 ratio between NFL quarterbacks and paramedics provide just one example of wealth disparity in America. The class system in America creates unfair income inequality that keeps the top living lucrative lives while the working class struggles to make ends meet. As long as the class system still exists in the way it currently operates, quality of life for families like mine will continue to be very poor. I think that it’s impossible to eliminate all inequality, but we can make changes to allow the working class to be able to work for improvement, and make the upper class play by the rules instead of controlling the entire country. Overall, while taking down the class system is a daunting task, it’s clear America needs to change in order for it to truly be the land of the free.

Social and financial class is a very complex subject and can be hard to understand. Overall, these three authors offer thoughtful insight into the very complex and intricate society in which we all live.  Taken together as a study for positive social and economic change, there is great value in moving toward a future that considers each viewpoint.

Power in America According to Doffhom vs Harari
	In any type of society, as learned through studying Sociology over the course of this semester, there is a hierarchy of power. In each society, the roles and functions of the so-called “power elite” differ, but the concept of power remains the same. Regardless of the time period, race, gender, or age, each individual experiences the effects of the “power elite”. This statement is proven by the works of Doffhom and Harari, as each describes what power looks like in different time periods and how power is established. While both authors discuss the same initial topic, the smaller factors that make up their individual definitions of power are described in different ways. Doffhom describes the “power elite” in America as the upper class that consists of active workers for-profit or nonprofit organizations while Harari argues that big corporations are continuously increasing in power, and will hold the most power over America in the near future. 
	Each author discusses the concept of power in different ways. In Doffhom’s argument, he describes political power of the elites over the lower class members of society, while Harari discusses the technological power that big corporations hold over the rest of society. The “power elites” are able to work their way into the government through their social and economic status, which allows them to make decisions for the country that directly contributes to their socioeconomic group. Harari explores how big corporations use their technological power to expand their own companies. For example, when Apple releases a new product, people wait outside in extreme temperatures for extended amounts of time hoping to be the first to snag the new iPhone. There are videos of customers trampling each other to get inside the building to spend a pretty penny on a device not much different from the last one. The ability to control hundreds of thousands of people with the release of a new product is baffling, and Harari explores how this type of situation is only the beginning of big corporations using their power to advance society in a way that benefits them. 
	Doffhom’s argument is focused around the upper class, “snobby” individuals that have money and a strong educational background. This elite group consists of CEOs, socialites, and executives that execute their power in the government. Although it seems that the government would have more control than a group of “daddy’s money Harvard alumni”, these individuals are able to intertwine themselves in the government system by becoming lawyers, judges, and even friends of individuals inside the government, and are able to tip the hat in a direction that directly benefits the elite group. Even research shows that members of the senate and congress for both political parties consist of members of the elite. Although the government claims to be “for the people, by the people”, it truly is to benefit the elite, by the elite. By tricking citizens to believe they are choosing who goes into office, what decisions are made, and more, citizens willingly give up their power, and hand it to the elite. 
Harari argues that the advancement of technology has allowed large companies to create an unspoken power of the citizens of America due to the fact that they are the most technologically advanced, and Americans have become obsessed with the new advancements granted by the creation of new algorithms. These algorithms essentially force individuals to give up their ability to make their own choices and allow AI to begin possessing the power of decision-making. Now more than ever, technology is advancing at a rapid pace, which in return, allows companies to make these large leaps towards an AI-centered lifestyle. Harari discusses how these corporations creating AI models of doctors and homes are removing the concept of free will from the lives of Americans. By interacting with these new forms of technology, Americans cannot be certain how much power is truly being stolen. As interaction with AI increases, the more that these models learn about individuals, and over time, will replace the individuals’ own conscious and begin making decisions for them. For example, Harari discusses how AI will eventually take over most jobs in society, ranging from cashiers to doctors. With no jobs available, individuals are forced into using their time doing other activities, however, this decision was not based upon free will, but technically, by force. Although having an AI model in homes or workplaces has it benefits, the more closely that individuals interact with these models, the more the models are able to learn about human consciousness, giving them more information to modify themselves, and essentially, know humanity more than humanity knows itself. 
In both scenarios, the lower class citizens are being robbed of their own sense of free will, and are being controlled by whoever is in power. The concept of power is not something that can be eliminated in society, as it is an essential factor for advancement, however, as the power is continuously being granted to the elite groups, the more they are able to advance. This is a vicious cycle that is almost impossible to escape, and the lower class groups are unaware of how they are fueling this hierarchy of power. 
Another obvious difference between the two author’s arguments about power is that Doffhom discusses how the government and corporations (and or business owners) are divided, while Harari explores how technological advancements could possibly grant corporations all the power, or that they could work together with the government as a unit. Doffham explores how many business leaders feel powerless in the face of the government, and how they feel unheard. There is an obvious rift between political leaders and business leaders, which fuels the government even more, because members are aware of how other groups feel threatened by the government. On the other hand, Harari explores how corporations and the government could possibly work hand in hand. Because AI is expected to take over many jobs in the future, it is not surprising that the government could potentially be controlled by AI models, which are controlled by big corporations, furthermore, gaining more power for these said corporations. By implementing AI in every aspect of individuals lives, the corporations that create them will gain power exponentially until houses, cars, and even individuals’ thoughts are controlled, monitored, and used for further advancements. 
Although both situations from each author is different, individuals are still trapped in the cycle that is power in America. Doffhom describes how socialites are able to sneak their way into government, but this process happens very publicly, and the people still believe that it is their decision. For example, by electing Donald Trump as President of the United States, the people believed they were making this choice, while in reality, Trump was already an individual of high status with the financial stability and connections that already included him somewhat in politics. Electing him as President was merely the last step to the plan to include the elites in the government. Soon after, it was released that Trump had elected some of his personal friends to serve in different areas of government, which supports Doffhom’s argument. 
Both Doffhom and Harari discuss how power allows individuals to believe they are making decisions for themselves, but in reality, individuals are forced to make a certain decision that has been provided by the ones in control. As Doffhom explains in his work, many members of the “power elite” are able to run for political office due to their connections and status. When the ballet is provided during the election season, Americans are able to choose between several different options of candidates, and between more than two political parties. However, each individual is typically one of these “power elites”, and therefore, the decision has already been made. An example of this is that every few years, Apple products begin to become glitchy and suddenly stop working. However, this typically occurs during two different events; either there was just a new software update or a new product is soon being released. Apple is able to force their users to buy new products when their old ones stop working. This is not by coincidence, but by the fact that Apple is such a large and successful company that it’s customers do not mind buying the “latest and greatest” product that they are offering. 
Regardless of time period, the hierarchy of power exists in any sort of functioning society. Doffhom and Harari show how generalizable the concept of power is in society, and provides two different examples of how power can be created and exerted upon the individuals not included in the group with power. Doffhom explains how the “power elites” have their power due to their wealth and status, and are able to exert this power by either becoming CEOs or members of the government, where they exert their power to benefit themselves. Harari discusses how big corporations are currently the most powerful due to their access to technological advances, and how the world will be effected by these new algorithms. While companies like Apple and Microsoft are now the most current technological “crazes” in the world, every day they are modifying these products to become better and better, which will result in these companies having the power to control every aspect of an individual’s life. With the rise of smart homes and talks of robots delivering UPS packages to front doors, I have no doubt in my mind that within 30 years, AI will have almost completely taken over inside the workplace. There will be Siri like robots that talk through devices catching people shoplifting, or diagnosing someone with cancer. There is a possibility as well that the concept of power will shift away from technology and towards another concept. Regardless of how it is presented and exerted, the concept of power will remain the same throughout any society.

I have worked many small part-time jobs, ice cream scooper, server, babysitter, volleyball coach, feed shop warehouse worker, farm hand, and most recently a metal worker for a golf company. Othering This can lead to people diminishing or belittling other groups and people, simply just because they are different. Othering can happen due to differences of race, gender, sexuality, nationality, religion, and many other characteristics. Othering contributes to social inequities and is a form of discrimination. The beauty myth is the idea that women are frequently under pressure to conform to specific beauty norms, such as being slender, having flawless skin, and donning cosmetics, just to achieve proper status in society. These concepts relate to my work experiences because the experiences described in both examples relate to the beauty myth and othering because they prove how society has constructed certain gender roles and expectations that limit women's opportunities and potential.

In my second puzzle, my male colleagues at the golf company treated me the only female employee differently, making sexist comments and belittling my abilities, even when I proved that I was capable and efficient in my work. This is another example of othering and the beauty myth, as the men in this case saw the me as an outsider, an object to be looked at or a lower-class worker, rather than an equal colleague with skills and abilities.
The problem with othering and the beauty myth is that it is deeply ingrained in our society and in the way we view others. The myth also holds the idea that women should be “seen and not heard.”  The myth is reflected by social media, advertising, pop culture, because all of these portray women as objects for men's desire, rather than personal individuals, with interests, skills, intelligence, and personalities.

In my experience I was denied a job opportunity because I was the “other” sex, so women might be subjected to loss job opportunities, promotions, and we also may be paid less than our male colleagues.
The issues of othering and the beauty myth are interconnected, and both contribute to the discrimination and belittling of women in society but especially in the workplace.
