Social Media and Its Negative Impact on Women 

	Social media has developed into a widely used platform of communication and connection between individuals around the world. The accessibility to online platforms has allowed for many adolescents and young women to interact with multiple applications that display the cultural norms on the appearance of females. What are the implications of the perception of beauty and body stereotypes? How does this affect individual body image of young women? Social media portrays the cultural norms and expectations that adolescents and young women are expected to maintain in relation to their physical appearance. The constant society pressure placed on women negatively impacts their physically and psychological well being. While social media is a benefit of access to information and quicker communication, it negatively impacts the identity of women on a consistent basis. This paper discusses how social media impacts promotes the standards of physical attractiveness leading to body dissatisfaction, a negative impact on identity, and increases the likelihood of eating disorders. 
	The topic of gender is discussed in “The Beauty Myth,” which seeks to reveal the social expectations for women to be physically beautiful. Wolf explains that female liberation is often hindered by a shift towards a feeling of negativity towards physical appearance. Despite women becoming more successful and gaining power throughout the feminist movements, many still felt hindered by feelings of self hatred and physical obsessions. As these ideas became more prevalent in society and through the development of technology, mass media campaigns created a significant force of societal pressure for women to conform to unrealistic standards. Due to the societal pressure, many women become preoccupied with these expectations, leading to the rise of eating disorders and plastic surgery in order to compete with the unattainable standards set by society. The rise of modern society lead to a display of images depicting how women are desired to look, thereby controlling women through ideals and stereotypes. 
	The pressure for women to conform to societal ideals of aesthetics means that there is constantly an expectation that women are forced to achieve. However, this is an unobtainable reality and leads to an attack on a young woman’s sense of self. This leads to dangerous implications in which young women become constantly dissatisfied with their physical appearance and oftentimes leads to drastic measures.  Social media enhances the impact on women’s identity by amplifying the cultural perception of women across all applications such as Facebook, Pinterest, and Instagram. Access to these forms has created a whole new world of interactions, except this time it is through a screen. Being behind a screen distorts the reality of the “beauty” that women are trying to achieve. Societal expectations are amplified because women are conditioned to believe that what is present on the screen is true. While this is oftentimes not the case, women misunderstand that the images on the screen are a distorted sense of reality. Without the understanding that many images presented on social media are often photoshopped or edited, women often believe that they must do what it takes in order to match the image on the screen. 
	The idea that “beauty is pain” leads to the perception in young women to implement extreme measures in order to combat struggles with self-image. These implications often come from examples of mass media that influence women’s perceptions of their own physical appearance. The “cultural icon of female beauty” for adolescents and women is the “Barbie doll” (Dittman 2009). The mass production of a toy often given to young girls represents an image of an ultra-thin woman. This leads to a desire to have a “thin” and perfect ideal body. As an individual continues to grow up, these ideas are amplified through social media depicting images of real-life women who look identical to the doll they once played with as a child. These ideas are also shown in magazines such as Sports Illustrated and Playboy, in which models epitomize the ideal female body shape. These real-world examples often lead to body dissatisfaction and a negative factor in relation to perceived body image. The idea often leads to women projecting negative feelings towards physical attributes of themselves and comparing themselves to peers who resemble these types of mass media images. 
	Another impact of body expectations presented through social media is through body image. Women often project a negative self attitude towards their size, shape, and physical aesthetics in relation to the norms presented by society that women are expected to obtain. These emotions are directed by how each woman’s self-perceived physical attributes relate to the negative evaluation of their overall appearance. In relation to the topic of gender, women often are dissatisfied and have a negative body image as they often view themselves as overweight, despite maintaining an average weight level. This perception is discussed in “The Looking Glass Self,” in which James Cooley describes the idea that how you feel about yourself is based on how you think others perceive you. Through social media, societal norms and expectations often lead to judgements on others that do not match the ideal standard of beauty. As mentioned previously, social media exists as a screen distorting that distorts the realities of life. Since the perceptions of oneself depends on the social context one is in, because social media translates these negative connotations of body image, women feel as though they do not conform to societal norms and therefore have a negative image of themselves. 
	Another aspect of social media that creates a negative impact on women’s identity is that apps design feeds that reflect individual preferences specific to each user. This has developed the capacity to bring the user into a new world, separate from reality. Because social media has become personal and sites shape to each individual user, one who is likely to look at models on Instagram is likely going to see those types of images everytime the app is accessed. This leads to an obsessive quality in which the user feels as though they should be engaged with the app constantly and indirectly, creating a negative impact on self worth. In addition, social media involves following peers, acquaintances, and influencers. While seeing models presented with a “perfect” body often leads to women feeling less happy with themselves, however, seeing individuals you know embody the societal norms often has a greater impact on negative self image. Social media has become the domain of peers in which women find it functional to compare themselves to others, likely those they often see in the hallways at school. The idea of comparison in these situations often leads to a negative affect. Everytime one posts on Instagram, yet the post has fewer “likes”  when compared to others, one often feels as though they are not enough which decreases self worth. This leads to a poor perception of self as one sees themselves based on what others might think and leads to destruction in their identity. 
A study conducted in 1997 discussed the idea of a “model trap,” which proposed that young girls often compare their physical attractiveness with that of advertising models. Being challenged by unrealistic expectations impacts self-perceptions of physical attractiveness and leads to individuals having a desire to become models. These concepts are often implemented in advertisements and tv commercials that convey the idea that female bodies are considered “objects” and their physical beauty determines their overall value. This idea is related to three viewpoints in which women find themselves when struggling with body image issues. The first is self evaluation, the judgment of value of one’s abilities and personal traits. Because women consider models to have “superior” physical attractiveness, one often compares themselves to individuals who are shaped to represent the ideal body image. This directly relates to negative self-perceptions and self-esteem. Secondly, one may focus on self-improvement. This is defined through an individual’s inspiration to better oneself through a particular attribute. Even as a child, individuals often compared themselves to a peer when learning how to perform tasks or reach a certain goal. This translates to women working to reach the same weight as a friend or comparing with others to reach a goal rather than focusing on their individual health and well-being. The last viewpoint is self enhancement, which is an individual's attempt to maintain positive views of oneself to protect self-esteem. These comparisons to others are often made in a downward connotation, meaning that individuals put down others in order to make them feel better about themselves. This is a very negative concept as many individuals often cyberbully others through social media because there is a screen blocking them from the hurtful words displayed. The response of self greatly impacts the extent of the negative nature women feel when they are fighting the battle of body dissatisfaction. 
Another implication of the effects of social media and its negative impacts on women is the development of eating disorders. While this is not a common result for most women, those who exhibit vulnerable characteristics such as low self-esteem, depression, perfectionism and internalization of physical expectations. This leads to an amplification in the desire to reach the “thin” level of ideal physical characteris. These negative thoughts can potentially lead to eating disorders in which women maintain unhealthy lifestyles hoping that they can reach the ideal body type. This can be found through the refusal to eat and maintain the appropriate body weight for age and height. Others often experience patterns of binging followed by fasting and overexercising to lessen caloric intake. These unhealthy lifestyles often stem from the unrealistic body image type displayed on social media. 
In conclusion, the online world of social media often influences the self perception of women in terms of physical appearance. As new technology continues to advance, powerful industries have created a massive impact on culture to reinforce these ideas of the “perfect” body. These articles show that “The Beauty Myth'' explains the underlying relationship of women with societal expectations to be physically beautiful. Throughout history, women have been subjected to a system of beliefs that controls women into maintaining aesthetic qualities that are unobtainable. The role of social media enhances these psychological and physical hardships on women by establishing a force of cultural pressures women have to maintain. Because of these ideals, women are willing to go to extreme measures and even maintain unhealthy lifestyles in order to achieve a “perfect body.” These implications often lead to severe negative effects on women’s mental health and sense of self worth.

The Effects of Hegemonic Masculinity
	Is hegemonic masculinity benefitting society’s youth? While current media and mainstream culture in recent western society are perpetuating the notion or practice of dominant, assertive, strong, and competitive masculine traits; moreover, it brings up the question, how is it affecting society’s youth? There are some in society that tends to belong to a higher social class who have certain racial, societal, gender-based, economic, and other privileges that would state that the messages or teachings of hegemonic masculinity towards the youth bring out breadwinners and overall successful men into functioning society.  In contrast, another side of society states that hegemonic masculinity is destructive to young boys and men because it maintains a toxic form of masculinity that not only affects men negatively but also women. After all, they can become victims of men who have been guided or influenced by the effects of this masculinity.
           Young men and boys who don’t fit into the direct mold that is placed for the type of man this masculinity maintains, are now put into a category lesser than the “ideal man”. I argue that those same men who are put in a lesser category because they aren’t the stereotypical dominant, controlling, and overachieving men that hegemonic masculinity expects; they become victims in society due to this idea of thought.
           One summer evening while Tita Carol was away doing some shopping, my Uncle Fred got drunk and started talking to us boys, my cousins, and me about “manly stuff”. He ended up discussing women in excruciating detail by vulgarly sexualizing and even degrading them and saying things such as, “You guys need to get women with meat on her bones, that’s how you’ll know she’ll feed you right” or “You guys need to gain a woman who’s a 6 or 7 because women who are 9’s and 10’s don’t stay too long”. Uncle Fred continued in a drunken stupor about how a woman’s ass is more important than boobs. While listening I ended up having a disgusted look on my face which my Uncle quickly called out. I explained to him that his comments didn’t feel right to me and how it asserts and perpetuates that women should be practically servants to men. He quickly responded by laughing at my face and told me that I’ll learn one day that he’s right, how I need to learn how to engage in locker-room talk and do more manly activities with them. My cousins sat there in silence while I listened to their father’s comments.
           Another similar event happened while staying at their house, on my 13th birthday we all decided to host a big Filipino party at my Tita’s. The party was going well until my Uncle Fred started drinking. I was outside playing with my cousins and other kids till he stopped drinking to strangely comment how my testicles would grow in and I’d start feeling certain ways toward women. I became so embarrassed because all the other kids and even their parents heard him talk to me that way. I soon went over to my mother and my Tita Carol tearing up and explaining what happened and they excused it by saying it was the alcohol talking and that he loves me. Both my mother and my Tita Carol are married to men who I know married them due to Asian fetishization and due to the effects of hegemonic masculinity. I truly believe both men do not think of them as equals. I soon went back outside wiping the tears off my face which my Uncle noticed and said, “Man up John. Men don’t cry” as he was rummaging through the garage fridge for more beer. I have been surrounded by a culture of hegemonic masculinity ever since my days as a young boy, and it is being perpetuated by not only the powerful men in my family but also the women who are victims of it as well.
           Brett Stoudt discusses in his article how these wealthy, upper-class white boys who attend a rich all-boys private school named Rockport and their experiences of violence in relation to the concept of hegemonic masculinity. For instance, the author concluded that hegemonic masculine attributes are beneficial to the privileged boys because it directly creates a culture of competition between all of the boys which motivated them to improve. However, while this form of masculinity can be beneficial, it is only beneficial to the young men who are surrounded by the environment, fit the mold, and are privileged enough to reap the benefits. Furthermore, this formation of competition rewards men who are privileged enough to be able to compete at the top, as the ideal successful man. Although, there is certainly a sense of impunity in place towards the men who fit the mold of hegemonic masculinity and their words and actions towards “lesser categories of people”.
           As I have stated before, my cousins have been more privileged than I have. They have had more economic advantages, social advantages, educational advantages, and other privileges than I ever will. Both of them have always worked well with the plans of my Uncle Fred and they especially check out all the categories for hegemonic masculinity. Moreover, like the Rockport boys, my cousins have benefitted due to the competitive effects of hegemonic masculine attributes they have learned from their father. My older cousin James always followed his Father’s words as if they are absolute and has become a man with hegemonic masculine values and attributes. He has always stayed consistent in his beliefs imparted to him from my Uncle Fred, that men must be at the very top, must be dominant, non-emotional, tough, competitive, and overall superior to women. It is the same for my younger cousin, Fred Jr. as I watch him grow up into his freshman year of high school. Their beliefs are perpetuated because they aren’t challenged by diverse mindsets and when they are exposed to those different mindsets they push them away.
           The youth of society who are inharmonious with the culture of hegemonic masculinity can grow up believing they are “lesser than” because they are forced into a position of a “lesser category” by these hegemonic masculine men and those who perpetuate this form of masculinity. Now, what can the people put these lesser categories do to stop this cycle? It is through educating oneself about these harmful stereotypes and how toxic they can be to others who don’t fit the mold of hegemonic masculinity, only then we can start working to create change.
